In this problem, minimum three elements are required. So, we start calculating no. of subarrays from 2nd index. If we find equal difference between last 3 consecutive numbers, we increase the count by 1 but if difference between last 4/5 consecutive numbers are equal then we just take no. of subarray of last index element and add 1 to it (since previous sequence is continue and 1 new sequence is coming).

Let's understand the logic through an example:
nums [] = 5,  8, 12, 16, 20, 24, 25, 28, 31
start with 2nd index:
**index -> num[i] - num[i-1] == num[i-1] - num[i-2] : count**
2 -> 12 - 8 (4) != 8-5 (4) : 0 
3 -> 16-12 (4) ==12-8(4) : 1
4 -> 20-16(4) == 16-12(4) : 1(previous index) + 1 = 2;
5 -> 24 -20(4) == 20-16(4) : 2 (previous index) +1 = 3;
6 -> 25 - 24 (1) != 24-10(4) : 0;
7 -> 28-25 (3) != 25-24(1) : 0;
8 -> 31-28 (3) == 28-25(3) : 1;

So, total no. of subarrays = 0+1+2+3+0+0+1 = 7

