# **Mathematical Solution**
***Fastest Solution***

*Logic for curr(curr-3)/2*
If there is an subarray, satisfying the conditions given, having ***N*** elements then
1. how many subarray of size 3 are possible from the given subarray = ***N - ( 3 - 1 )***
2. how many subarray of size 4 are possible from the given subarray = ***N - ( 4 - 1 )***
3. how many subarray of size 5 are possible from the given subarray = ***N - ( 5 - 1 )***
.
.
.
.
N.how many subarray of size N are possible from the given subarray = ***N - ( N - 1 )***

which will sum to ***N * ( N - 2) + ( N - 1 ) * N /2***  = ***N * ( N - 3 ) / 2***

```
class Solution {
public:
    int numberOfArithmeticSlices(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n = nums.size();
        for(int i=0;i<n-1;i++)nums[i]-=nums[i+1];
        // for(auto i:nums)cout<<i<<" ";
        int curr=1;
        int ans=0;
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++)
        {
            if(nums[i]==nums[i-1])curr++;
            else{
                curr++;     //adding 1 to current because the actual value of curr will always be 
							//one less since we are leaving out the first element of the subset in calculation
							// for eg : {2,4,6,8,11,12,14} will have the auxiliary array as {-2,-2,-2,-3,-1,-2,14}
							//so three consecutive -2 will depict {2,4,6,8} hence the curr++
                ans += ((curr*(curr-3))/2)+1;
                curr=1;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```


