# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The first idea that can visit the head is a classic DP solution:
```
class Solution {
    public int numberOfArithmeticSlices(int[] nums) {
        int result = 0;
        int[] dp = new int[nums.length];
        for (int i = 2; i < nums.length; i++) {
            if (nums[i] - nums[i - 1] == nums[i - 1] - nums[i - 2]) {
                dp[i] = dp[i - 1] + 1;
                result += dp[i];
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```
Where time complexity is $$O(n)$$ and space complexity is $$O(n)$$

# But!
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We can store the entire **dp** array in the **nums** array and it will look like this:
```
class Solution {
    public int numberOfArithmeticSlices(int[] nums) {
        if (nums.length < 3) {
            return 0;
        }
        int result = 0;

        int diff = nums[1] - nums[0];
        nums[0] = 0;
        for (int i = 2; i < nums.length; i++) {
            int temp = nums[i] - nums[i - 1];
            if (temp == diff) {
                nums[i-1] = nums[i-2] + 1;
                result += nums[i-1];
            } else {
                nums[i-1] = 0;
                diff = temp;
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```
Where time complexity is $$O(n)$$ and space complexity is $$O(1)$$. Much better, but... looks ugly. 
Here we need to ask the question, do we need to store the entire DP array at all? Nope!
# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int numberOfArithmeticSlices(int[] nums) {
        int result = 0;
        int counter = 0;
        for (int i = 2; i < nums.length; i++) {
            if (nums[i - 1] - nums[i - 2] == nums[i] - nums[i - 1]) {
                counter++;
                result += counter;
            } else {
                counter = 0;
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

Or using the ternary operator:
```
class Solution {
    public int numberOfArithmeticSlices(int[] nums) {
        int result = 0;
        int counter = 0;
        for (int i = 2; i < nums.length; i++) {
            counter = nums[i - 1] - nums[i - 2] == nums[i] - nums[i - 1]? counter + 1: 0;
            result += counter;
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```
The complexity of time and space is still O(n) and O(1), respectively.
