I provide two solutions here, **Brute Force** and **DP**. I think brute force is pretty much straightforward so we can come up w/ brute force solution during the interview first.

  **Intuition**
  We simply try all the combination within a nested for-loop.

  ```
  class Solution 
{
    public int numberOfArithmeticSlices(int[] nums)
    {
        // O(n^2) time | O(1) space
        if(nums == null || nums.length <= 2)    return 0;

        int res = 0;

        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length-2; i++)
        {
            int diff = nums[i+1] - nums[i];

            for(int j = i+2; j < nums.length; j++)
            {
                if(nums[j] - nums[j-1] == diff)
                    res += 1;
                else
                    break;
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```

**Intuition**
For DP, we need to use an equation `dp[i] = dp[i-1] + 1`. Let's see the example below if `nums[ ] = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]`

```
[1, 2, 3]       --> [1, 2, 3] --> 1 combination.
[1, 2, 3, 4]    --> [2, 3, 4] and [1, 2, 3, 4] --> 2 more combinations
[1, 2, 3, 4, 5] --> [3, 4, 5], [2, 3, 4, 5], and [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] --> 3 more combinations.
```
Therefor, `sum += dp[i]` gives us all the possible combinations.

```
class Solution 
{
    public int numberOfArithmeticSlices(int[] nums)
    {
        // O(n) time | O(n) space
        if(nums == null || nums.length <= 2)    return 0;

        // dp[i] represents to how many arithmetic sequences during the range [0,i]
        int[] dp = new int[nums.length];
        int res = 0;

        for(int i = 2; i < nums.length; i++)
        {
            if(nums[i] - nums[i-1] == nums[i-1] - nums[i-2])
                dp[i] = dp[i-1] + 1;

            res += dp[i];
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```

