idea is to take a window of 3 three adjacent numbers with same common diff and try to entend the window 
as far as possible . and while extending the window check if the window size >= 3 , if yes then for every iteration of extending the window we will have = i - 2 - start + 1 sub arrays , this formula is an observation

idea for formula is that conisder [1,2,3,4]
for i == 2 , we need 3 numbers , ie the number should start for i - 2 ie 0 
so for i = 2 and start = 0 how many windows we can have of size 3 ? 
[1,2,3] , i - 2 - start + 1  = 1 subarray

again for i = 3 we need atleast 3 numbers in window , we can have more but we need minimum 3 number so how many windows we can have for i = 3 and start = 0 ?
[1 , 2 ,3 ,4 ] , [2 , 3 , 4]  , i - 2 - start + 1  = 2 subarray

 so see for any i if we know the start index from where the window might start we can have atmost i - 2 - start + 1
 windows 

 now the ans would be the sum of  number of all such sub arrays for every valid i  

 this is similar to asking -> given an index i and a starting position , how may sub arrays can be formed which include the index i 

 consider -> [1,2,3,4]  , s = 0  and i = 2 

 we can see there are 3 subarays [1,2,3] , [2,3] and [3]  which include i = 2 and the number is is equal to i - s + 1 

 so for every valid i in a series we need to calculate the all such subaraays which include i - 2 th index starting from 
 the beginning index of the series 
 and ans is the cumulative sum of all such sub arrays

```
class Solution {
    public int numberOfArithmeticSlices(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length ;
        if(n < 3)
            return 0 ;
        int cnt = 0 , start = 0;
        for(int i = 1 ; i < n ; i++){

            if(i + 1 < n && nums[i] - nums[i - 1] == nums[i + 1] - nums[i]){
                start = i - 1;

				// try to extend the window as far as possible while the condition is satisfied 

                while(i + 1 < n && nums[i] - nums[i - 1] == nums[i + 1] - nums[i]){
                    i++;
                    if(i - start + 1 > 2)
                        cnt += i - 2 - start + 1;
                }
            }
        }
        return cnt ;
    }
}
```

